The selectivity of the method was investigated by examining the change of fluorescence intensity of CDs in the presence of PA, nitro compounds, phenolic compounds [39] (PHE, TNT, NB, 2,4-DNP, 2,4-DPH, o-DHB, p-DHB, o-NP, m-NP, and p-NP, detailed information of these compounds were listed in Table 1
                        ), and metal ions. These results are listed in Fig. 8
                        a and b. In the one hand, determination of PA by carbon nanodots is highly specific. PA, nitro compounds, and phenolic compounds were all selected to study the fluorescence performance of the carbon nanodots. As Fig. 8a shows, the first group in this bar chart present the fluorescence intensity of carbon dots with (black) or without PA (red). The other black bars present the emission signals of carbon dots in the presence of nitro compounds or phenolic compounds respectively. It is clear that compared with obvious fluorescence quenching by PA, the fluorescence intensity of carbon nanodots does not changed by the addition of other compounds, indicating that the selectivity of this method is perfect. On the other hand, the nitro compounds or phenolic compounds have slight influences on fluorescence intensity of carbon nanodots in the presence of PA, which means that the approved method for the determination of PA have good anti-jamming capability. It is clear that this method exhibits superiority to previously reported methods in terms of sensitivity, selectivity, and rapidity of PA determination (Table 2
                        ), which guarantees the detection of PA in water samples.
